******
[1] News report
Date: Fri 11 Jun 2010
Source: The Mainichi Daily News [edited]
<http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20100611p2a00m0na008000c.html>


Foot-and-mouth infections confirmed in 2 more Miyazaki cities
-------------------------------------------------------------
In the wake of suspected cases of foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] in the
Miyazaki beef cattle center of Miyakonojo, infections were also
confirmed on 10 Jun 2010 in the cities of Miyazaki and Hyuga.

Both cities have started slaughtering and burying livestock, as
officials struggle to control the highly contagious disease.

In Miyazaki, the disease was confirmed at a farm with 1325 pigs, while
it hit a farm with 349 head of cattle in Hyuga.

The Miyazaki Municipal Government has decided to close the Ikime no
Mori sports park, located near the area where the infections broke
out. Annually, some 260 000 people visit the park, which has tennis
courts and a stadium used for training by baseball teams including the
Fukuoka Softbank Hawks [a baseball team].

"It's near the area where the disease occurred, and the measure was
taken to control the spread of infections. The baseball field will
probably not be available for the prefectural high school baseball
tournament," a municipal government representative said.

In the city of Hyuga, 100 workers and supporters including 13
veterinarians were dispatched to handle the disease. Officials said
they hoped to finish all related work on 11 Jun 2010.

The Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare and the Miyazaki Prefectural
Government have made efforts to contain the disease following
outbreaks in central Miyazaki Prefecture, introducing restrictions on
movement of cattle and pigs.

Livestock within a 10km [6 mi] radius of farms that have been hit by
the disease have been vaccinated to slow the spread of infection
before being slaughtered. In other areas within a 20km [12 mi] radius,
livestock numbers have been reduced through outbound shipments to
create a buffer zone, preventing infections from spreading between
cattle.

Sterilizing points have also been set up at various points along main
roads, where cars are disinfected. Since 4 Jun 2010, when restrictions
were lifted on cattle in Ebino in western Miyazaki Prefecture, new
suspected infections had appeared to be decreasing, and it was
believed that vaccines had been effective in controlling the disease.

It was after this that the suspected case was reported in Miyakonojo.

Masafumi Mukamoto, an associate professor at Osaka Prefecture
University, said people and vehicles may be responsible. "Looking at
the distances involved, it is highly probable that people and vehicles
have carried the virus. After the animals are vaccinated, symptoms of
the disease don't easily show up even if they are infected. When
people come into contact with these cows they can carry the virus
without knowing it."

Hiroomi Akashi, a professor in veterinary virology at the University
of Tokyo also believes that vehicles have aided the spread of the
disease. He said thorough sterilization ['disinfection' may be the
preferable term. - Mod.AS] measures were needed.

"The latest weekly animal hygiene report of the Ministry of
Agriculture Forestry and Fisheries introduces cases in which
sterilizing work has not been properly carried out after vaccinations
have been performed. If that's true, there may be a connection with
the latest infections. There's a need to provide thorough
sterilization once again," he said.

At present there remain about 30 000 head of cattle that are due to be
slaughtered but have not been culled yet. Furthermore, much work
remains in the process of shipping out cattle to create the buffer zone.

--
