******
[2] news report
Date: Fri 11 Jun 2010
Source: iStockAnalyst, Kyodo News International report [edited]
<http://www.istockanalyst.com/article/viewiStockNews/articleid/4201846>


Prime minister Naoto Kan said Friday [11 Jun 010] he will visit
Miyazaki Prefecture on Saturday [12 Jun 2010] as part of the
government's efforts to contain the continuing spread of FMD among
livestock in the southwestern Japanese prefecture.

"Regrettably, the situation is severe," Kan said at a meeting of the
government task force to tackle the problem. "It is important to
contain (the disease) in an initial response. We will do everything we
can."

On Friday [11 Jun 2010], the Miyazaki prefectural government said cows
and pigs in the cities of Miyazaki, Hyuga, and Saito tested positive
in genetic tests [PCR -- see OIE report below] for the highly
contagious disease, showing that the infection has spread within the
prefecture and beyond the area where it was initially concentrated.

The prefecture has already started slaughtering about 220 livestock
bred in farms where the cows and pigs were raised, after they were
found the previous day to show suspected symptoms of infection.

At its meeting in Tokyo, the government task force analyzed that the
disease has spread mainly due to lack of places to bury the
slaughtered livestock, leading the local government to keep about 12
000 cows and some 19 000 pigs alive in the hardest-hit town of
Kawaminami after they were vaccinated.

The central government confirmed it will make efforts to hastily cull
livestock after finding places to bury them in order to prevent the
disease from spreading further. [See BBC News picture of 11 Jun 2010,
showing "Workers digging large holes (landfills) to bury slaughtered
cattle and pigs to prevent the spread of foot-and-mouth disease in
Miyakonojo in Miyazaki prefecture, Japan", at
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/10294452.stm>. - Mod.AS]

It also decided to reinforce disinfection work on roads and national
highways in the region amid the increasing risk of the disease
spreading to neighboring prefectures such as Kagoshima.

The Kagoshima prefectural government plans to block roads connecting
disease-hit Miyakonojo in Miyazaki Prefecture with 3 cities in
Kagoshima Prefecture, including Soo, one of Japan's largest livestock
industry centers, as early as Friday [11 Jun 2010] afternoon,
according to local officials.

MAFF [Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries] Minister
Masahiko Yamada told reporters after the task force meeting that
burying the slaughtered livestock in cities of Hyuga, Miyazaki and
Saito -- where the infection was newly found -- will be completed
within Friday [11 Jun 2010].

--
