******
[3] OIE report
Date: Thu 10 Jun 2010
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly
disease information 2010; 23(23) [summ. & edited]
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=9337>


Foot-and-mouth disease, Japan: follow-up report no. 8
-----------------------------------------------------
The information in the follow-up report at the URL above, submitted 10
Jun 2010 [thus before the detection of the new cases in Miyakonojo. -
Mod.AS] provides data on 26 new outbreaks, including their respective
numbers of susceptible and sick animals, their species, dates of
vaccination etc; for these details and an interactive map, subscribers
are referred to the full text at the URL above.

The report also includes the following epidemiological comment:
"All the cases had been confirmed by PCR until 1 Jun 2010. However,
since 2 Jun 2010, suspicious animals showing typical clinical signs of
FMD at farms located in the movement control area around
Kawaminami-cho have been officially recognized as FMD cases without
PCR for rapid identification and response. There have been a lot of
outbreaks in the area and it is indicated that the correlation between
typical clinical signs of FMD and PCR results is extremely high.
Suspicious animals without typical clinical signs or kept in other
areas have been confirmed by PCR as before.

Disposal of vaccinated animals started on 5 Jun 2010. The vaccination
has been performed from the rim to the centre of the area since 22 May
2010, giving more prioritiy to pigs than cattle, and was almost
complete by 26 May 2010.

As of 4 Jun 2010, a movement restriction around Ebino city was lifted
because there has been no outbreak in the area since 13 May 2010 and
the absence was demonstrated by active clinical and serological
surveillance targeted at all susceptible domestic animals in the area.
No animals are vaccinated in the area."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The involvement of Japan's prime minister in the FMD problem,
demonstrated also by his plan to visit tomorrow (12 Jun 2010) the
affected area, is another reminder of the major FMD epizootic in the
UK in 2001. At that time, national elections were postponed and the
PM, Tony Blair, was intensively involved in the control efforts and
the recruitment of the army to assist in the eradication activities.
The "Lessons to be learned" report, pertaining to the 2001 UK FMD
epizootic, is available at
<http://archive.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/fmd/fmd_report/report/index.htm>.
- Mod.AS]
